<elevation box="[457,515,875,899]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="m" value="27.0">
<quantity box="[457,515,875,899]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="m" value="27.0">27 m</quantity>
</elevation>
respectively (
<figureCitation box="[675,759,874,899]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="68.[151,250,1830,1852]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,206,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@68.[151,1436,193,1825]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="FIGURE 61. Distribution map of Sculpsitechinus auritus recorded in this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617575/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
). Bathymetric range of this species in Sri Lanka is 
<elevation box="[1343,1432,875,899]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="m" value="15.0" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="1.0">
<quantity box="[1343,1432,875,899]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="m" value="15.0" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="1.0">1–29 m</quantity>
</elevation>
. This species was first recorded in Sri Lanka by 
<bibRefCitation author="Doderlein, L." box="[684,881,910,935]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="821 - 846" refId="ref34633" refString="Doderlein, L. (1888) Echinodermen von Ceylon. Bericht uber die von den Herren Dres Sarasin gesammelten Asteroidea, Ophiuroidea und Echinoidea. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Abteilung fur Systematik, Geographie und Biologie der Tiere, 3, 821 - 846. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 1933" type="journal article" year="1888">Döderlein (1888)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,151,1403]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,946,971]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Remarks.</emphasis>
In contrast to Stara &amp; Sanciu’s (
<bibRefCitation author="Stara, P. &amp; Sanciu, L." box="[675,734,947,971]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="291 - 358" refId="ref36243" refString="Stara, P. &amp; Sanciu, L. (2014) Analysis of some astriclypeids (Echinoidea: Clypeasteroida). Biodiversity Journal, 5, 291 - 358." type="journal article" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
) description, Sri Lankan 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" box="[1015,1122,947,971]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="auritus">
<emphasis box="[1015,1122,947,971]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">S. auritus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two pairs of ambulacral plates between the petal tips and lunules. The periproct is close to the posterior margin (mean=16% TL). However, in Stara &amp; Sanciu’s (
<bibRefCitation author="Stara, P. &amp; Sanciu, L." box="[387,446,1019,1043]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="291 - 358" refId="ref36243" refString="Stara, P. &amp; Sanciu, L. (2014) Analysis of some astriclypeids (Echinoidea: Clypeasteroida). Biodiversity Journal, 5, 291 - 358." type="journal article" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
) examples, there are four to five pairs of plates between the petal tips and lunules, and the periproct is farther from the posterior margin (mean=21% TL).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,151,1403]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Specimen WUSL/EI/58, collected at a depth of 
<quantity box="[747,806,1091,1115]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="m" value="12.0">12 m</quantity>
from Palagala reef (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1108,1090,1115]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[223,1380,300,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of collection localities (BT1—Baththalangunduwa 1, BT2—Baththalangunduwa 2, CA—Casuarina Beach, CH—Chaddy Beach, ET—Etalai, HM—Hambantota, HR—Hiriketiya, KL—Kalmunai, KM—Kamburugamuwa, KT—Kattankudy, KI—Kirinda, MN—Mandathiv, MR—Marawila, ML—Mount Lavinia, MU—Mulathiv, NE1—Negombo 1, NE2—Negombo 2, NL—Nilwella, PE—Periyapaduwa, PO—Polhena, SL—Silavathurai, TB—Thennadi Bay, TR—Trincomalee, VL—Velvatithurai; see Appendix 1 for more information)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617462/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) on the western coast of 
<collectingCountry name="Sri Lanka" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
, differs from the material described above and may represent a different species (or a hybrid). In contrast to typical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" box="[236,345,1163,1187]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="auritus">
<emphasis box="[236,345,1163,1187]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">S. auritus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it has 1) a distinct anterior notch, 2) wide interporiferous zones (4–5% TL), and 3) a markedly structured oral side like in fossil 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L.Agassiz" authorityYear="1840" box="[517,631,1198,1223]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Amphiope" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[517,631,1198,1223]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Amphiope</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[645,781,1198,1223]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="67.[151,250,1419,1441]" captionTargetBox="[209,1378,193,1398]" captionTargetId="figure@67.[209,1378,193,1398]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURE 60. Sculpsitechinus auritus (A and C, WUSL/EI/59) and Sculpsitechinus sp. (B and D, WUSL/EI/58): A–B, aboral and C–D, oral views." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617573/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 60B, D</figureCitation>
; in contrast to the rather flattened oral surface of typical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="auritus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">S. auritus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Specimen WUSL/E1/58 is provisionally identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stara &amp; Sanciu" authorityYear="2014" box="[923,1097,1234,1259]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[923,1097,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Sculpsitechinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. until more material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stara &amp; Sanciu" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,325,1270,1295]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,325,1270,1295]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Sculpsitechinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[402,516,1270,1295]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
becomes available and the degree of intraspecific variation of the Sri Lankan population is better understood.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,151,1403]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" box="[199,307,1343,1367]" class="Echinoidea" family="Astriclypeidae" genus="Sculpsitechinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="auritus">
<emphasis box="[199,307,1343,1367]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">S. auritus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from other astriclypeids occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1158,1342,1367]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1174,1355,1342,1367]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="bisperforatus">
<emphasis box="[1174,1355,1342,1367]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">E. bisperforatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="truncatus">
<emphasis box="[1412,1436,1344,1367]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">E.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[187,292,1380,1403]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">truncatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by its open lunules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
